#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:1
msgid "Horizontal Scaling"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:3
msgid ""
"This is a collection of notes on scaling different Lemmy components "
"horizontally. This is not meant as a step-by-step guide, rather as general "
"tips and knowledge that might be useful to somebody who is already familiar "
"with and horizontal scaling concepts and best practices. If you don't "
"already know about concepts like load balancing, object storage, and reverse "
"proxies, then this document will probably be hard (or impossible) to "
"understand."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:5
msgid ""
"**Note: scaling Lemmy this way is not necessary, and for small instances, "
"the added overhead most likely outweighs any benefits.**"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:7
msgid "Why scale horizontally?"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:9
msgid ""
"If one of your Lemmy servers dies for any reason, your instance can still "
"remain operational"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:10
msgid ""
"Having multiple Lemmy servers allows you to do rolling upgrades (no downtime "
"needed to upgrade Lemmy!)"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:11
msgid ""
"Horizontal scaling provides additional flexibility in how you upgrade your "
"infrastructure"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:12
msgid ""
"As of Lemmy version 0.18.2, Lemmy appears to be able to use the same "
"resources more efficiently if they are split between multiple Lemmy processes"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:14
msgid "Breakdown of Lemmy components"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:16
msgid ""
"See [Lemmy components](administration.md#lemmy-components) for a high level "
"overview of what each component does."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:18
msgid "Lemmy-ui"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:20
msgid ""
"Lemmy-ui can be horizontally scaled, but make sure you read the following "
"section for information about rolling upgrades."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:22
#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:102
msgid "Rolling upgrades"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:24
msgid ""
"In general, there is nothing preventing you from running multiple load "
"balanced Lemmy-ui servers in parallel, but without some custom "
"configuration, **rolling upgrades will break Lemmy for your users!** This is "
"because by default, Lemmy-ui will serve static files through the express "
"process."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:26
msgid ""
"Consider the scenario where you have 2 Lemmy-ui servers, one is running on "
"version 1, and the other has just come online running version 2. A user "
"opening your Lemmy in their browser might have their front page html request "
"routed to version 1. This html will contain a reference to many other static "
"files which are specific to version 1. Most likely, some of these requests "
"will get routed to the server running version 2. **The files will not exist "
"on this server, the server will respond with 404, and the UI will remain in "
"a broken state.**"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:28
msgid "There are a few ways to work around this issue:"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:30
msgid ""
"The safest option is to ensure that all servers are able to serve static "
"files for all currently active Lemmy-ui versions."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:31
msgid ""
"There are many ways to achieve this, the most obvious one being to upload "
"your static files to object storage, and have reverse proxies route static "
"file requests to your static files bucket."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:32
msgid "Here's one possible example of how to do this with nginx:"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:34
msgid ""
"```\n"
"location /static {\n"
"   expires 1y;\n"
"   add_header Cache-Control \"public\";\n"
"   proxy_pass https://${bucket_fqdn};\n"
"\n"
"   limit_except GET {\n"
"       deny  all;\n"
"   }\n"
"\n"
"   proxy_intercept_errors on;\n"
"   # invalid keys result in 403\n"
"   error_page 403 =404 /@404static;\n"
"}\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:50
msgid ""
"Replace `${bucket_fqdn}` with the URL to your bucket. With this setup, you "
"should upload the contents of the lemmy-ui `dist/` directory to a "
"\"directory\" named `static/$LEMMY_UI_HASH` in your bucket, where the hash "
"is calculated from the commit you are deploying: `export LEMMY_UI_HASH=$(git "
"rev-parse --short HEAD)`. Note that this setup requires public acl on "
"uploaded files, so it's recommended to limit access to your bucket with an "
"IP allowlist policy."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:52
msgid ""
"An alternative option is to configure sticky sessions in your load balancer. "
"This will ensure that subsequent requests all end up on the same Lemmy-ui "
"server, and as long as your sticky sessions last longer than your upgrade "
"process, most clients should remain functional."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:53
msgid ""
"Similarly to sticky sessions, another possibility is to configure ip hash "
"based load balancing."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:54
msgid ""
"There is always the option to just employ downtime and upgrade all servers "
"at once (but that's not very fun!)"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:56
msgid "Lemmy_server"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:58
msgid "Lemmy_server can be horizontally scaled, with a few caveats."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:60
msgid ""
"Here's a quick example on how you could start 3 web servers, 3 federation "
"servers and one scheduled task process:"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:67
msgid ""
"Or run the Docker container with the `-e LEMMY_DISABLE_HTTP_SERVER=true` and "
"`-e LEMMY_DISABLE_ACTIVITY_SENDING=true` ENV parameters."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:76
msgid ""
"Or run the Docker containers with the `-e "
"LEMMY_DISABLE_ACTIVITY_SENDING=true` and `-e "
"LEMMY_DISABLE_SCHEDULED_TASKS=true` ENV parameters."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:85
msgid ""
"Or run the Docker containers with the `-e LEMMY_DISABLE_HTTP_SERVER=true`, `-"
"e LEMMY_DISABLE_SCHEDULED_TASKS=true`, `-e LEMMY_FEDERATE_PROCESS_INDEX=1` "
"and `-e LEMMY_FEDERATE_PROCESS_COUNT=3` ENV parameters."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:87
msgid "Scheduled tasks"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:89
msgid ""
"By default, a Lemmy_server process will run background scheduled tasks, "
"which must be run only on one server. Launching multiple processes with the "
"default configuration will result in multiple duplicated scheduled tasks all "
"starting at the same moment and trying to do the same thing at once."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:91
msgid ""
"To solve this, Lemmy must be started with the `--disable-scheduled-tasks` "
"flag (or `LEMMY_DISABLE_SCHEDULED_TASKS=true`) on all but one instance. In "
"general, there are two approaches:"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:93
msgid ""
"Run all your load balanced Lemmy servers with the `--disable-scheduled-"
"tasks` flag, and run one additional Lemmy server without this flag which is "
"not in your load balancer and does not accept any HTTP traffic."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:94
msgid ""
"Run one load balanced Lemmy server without the flag, and all other load "
"balanced servers with the flag."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:96
msgid "Federation queue"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:98
msgid ""
"The persistent federation queue (since 0.19) is split by federated domain "
"and can be processed in equal-size parts run in separate processes. To split "
"the queue up into N processes numbered 1...N, use the arguments `--federate-"
"process-index=i --federate-process-count=N` on each (or "
"`LEMMY_FEDERATE_PROCESS_INDEX=i` and `LEMMY_FEDERATE_PROCESS_COUNT=N` "
"respectively). It is important that each index is is given to exactly one "
"process, otherwise you will get undefined behaviour (missing, dupe "
"federation, crashes)."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:100
msgid ""
"Federation processes can be started and stopped at will. They will restart "
"federation to each instance from the last transmitted activity regardless of "
"downtime."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:104
msgid ""
"For most versions, rolling releases have been completely OK, but there have "
"been some cases where a database migration slips in which is NOT backwards "
"compatible (causing any servers running the older version of Lemmy to "
"potentially start generating errors). To be safe, you should always first "
"take a look at [what database migrations are included in a new version]"
"(https://github.com/LemmyNet/lemmy/tree/main/migrations), and evaluate "
"whether the changes are for sure safe to apply with running servers."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:106
msgid ""
"Note that even if there are no backwards incompatible migrations between "
"immediate version upgrades (version 1 -> 2 is safe and 2 -> 3 is safe), "
"doing bigger upgrades might cause these same migrations to become backwards "
"incompatible (a server running version 1 might not be compatible with "
"migrations from version 3 in this scenario). **It is generally best to only "
"upgrade one version at a time!**."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:108
msgid ""
"For the scheduled task process, it shouldn't cause any major issues to have "
"two servers running in parallel for a short duration during an upgrade, but "
"shutting the old one down before starting the new one will always be safer."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:110
msgid "Pict-rs"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:112
msgid ""
"Pict-rs does not scale horizontally as of writing this document. This is due "
"to a dependency on a Sled database, which is a disk based database file."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:114
msgid ""
"The developer of pict-rs has mentioned plans to eventually add Postgres "
"support (which should in theory enable horizontal scaling), but work on this "
"has not yet started."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:116
msgid ""
"Note that by caching pict-rs images (for example, with nginx, or with a "
"CDN), you can really minimize load on the pict-rs server!"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:118
msgid "Other tips"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:120
msgid ""
"Your lemmy-ui servers need to access your backend as well. If you don't want "
"a complicated setup with multiple load balancers, you could just have each "
"of your servers contain nginx, lemmy-ui, and lemmy_server, and just load "
"balance to an nginx on each of your servers"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:121
msgid ""
"Make sure you're passing the real client ip address to Lemmy, otherwise "
"Lemmy's built in rate limiter will trigger very often (if it rate limits "
"based on your load balancer's IP address, for example). With nginx, you "
"should use something like this in your nginx.conf:"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:129
msgid ""
"The internal Lemmy load balancer works based on an in-memory storage of ip "
"addresses. That means that by adding more Lemmy servers, you are effectively "
"making your rate limits less strict. If you rely on the built in limiter, "
"make sure to adjust the limits accordingly!"
msgstr ""
